<subSubSection id="6E8F6559FFE31017F7BD8C06AA09A0BF" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="262A36D2FFE31017F7BD8C06AA09A0BF" blockId="4.[151,1437,1346,1949]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis id="14E1EAC0FFE31017F7BD8C06AA74A39F" bold="true" box="[199,328,1382,1408]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Etymology</emphasis>
: The specific epithet ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="E1954D51FFE31017F52B8C06A9F5A39F" authorityName="Barahona-Segovia &amp; Guzmán &amp; Barceló &amp; Pañinao-Monsálvez" authorityYear="2020" box="[593,713,1382,1408]" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Ogcodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kunkunche">
<emphasis id="14E1EAC0FFE31017F52B8C06A9F5A39F" box="[593,713,1382,1408]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">kunkunche</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ refers to the southern Mapuche people named ‘Cuncos’. The “cuncos” or “puncos” (in mapudungun language = 
<taxonomicName id="E1954D51FFE31017F5948CEAA85AA3BB" authorityName="Barahona-Segovia &amp; Guzmán &amp; Barceló &amp; Pañinao-Monsálvez" authorityYear="2020" box="[750,870,1418,1444]" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Ogcodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kunkunche">
<emphasis id="14E1EAC0FFE31017F5948CEAA85AA3BB" box="[750,870,1418,1444]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">kunkunche</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) were a sedentary indigenous people, frequently considered to be the southern-most branch of the Mapuche people. They lived in southern 
<collectingCountry id="5E827642FFE31017F3ED8CCEAFE8A3D7" box="[1175,1236,1454,1480]" name="Chile" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Chile</collectingCountry>
from the Maullín River to the northern part of Chiloé and the neighboring islands. This indigenous people developed agriculture, cultivating several crops including potatoes and corn. Also, they were dedicated to recollecting marine mollusks and hunting marine fishes, sea lions and other marine mammals. The name “ 
<taxonomicName id="E1954D51FFE31017F4BC8F7AAF02A02B" authorityName="Barahona-Segovia &amp; Guzmán &amp; Barceló &amp; Pañinao-Monsálvez" authorityYear="2020" box="[966,1086,1562,1588]" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Ogcodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kunkunche">
<emphasis id="14E1EAC0FFE31017F4BC8F7AAF02A02B" box="[966,1086,1562,1588]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">kunkunche</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” was chosen for this spider fly species because this indigenous people were the group most hostile to the Spanish colonizers, and this represents the persistence of the new species described herein in the fragmented landscape that currently dominates the main Chiloé Island.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6E8F6559FFE31017F7BD8FC9AFCAA0DB" box="[199,1270,1705,1733]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="262A36D2FFE31017F7BD8FC9AFCAA0DB" blockId="4.[151,1437,1346,1949]" box="[199,1270,1705,1733]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis id="14E1EAC0FFE31017F7BD8FC9AA65A0DB" bold="true" box="[199,345,1705,1732]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Distribution</emphasis>
: Caulín, 
<geoCoordinate id="43A15015FFE31017F6BB8FCAA967A0DB" box="[449,603,1706,1732]" degrees="41.816013" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" precision="1" value="-41.816013">41.816013° S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="43A15015FFE31017F5128FC9A837A0DA" box="[616,779,1705,1733]" degrees="73.596358" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" precision="1" value="-73.59636">73.596358° W</geoCoordinate>
, 
<quantity id="E16D9B37FFE31017F46C8FCAA86DA0DA" box="[790,849,1706,1733]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" unit="m" value="48.0">48 m</quantity>
, Chacao, main Chiloé Island (
<figureCitation id="BEAE2A57FFE31017F3D98FCAAFD9A0DB" box="[1187,1253,1706,1732]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1545,1570]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,531,1514]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1435,525,1520]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distribution maps of the five Chilean species of Ogcodes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3831698" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3831698/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6E8F6559FFE31017F7BD8FAEAE4BA183" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="262A36D2FFE31017F7BD8FAEA8AEA14B" blockId="4.[151,1437,1346,1949]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis id="14E1EAC0FFE31017F7BD8FAEAA01A0F7" bold="true" box="[199,317,1742,1768]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Remarks:</emphasis>
Currently, Caulín is a rural town located in northern Chiloé Island with fragmented native forest cleared for livestock, grassland or crop use. The remaining forest is mainly secondary growth, composed primarily by 
<taxonomicName id="E1954D51FFE31017F7C18E77AA72A12F" box="[187,334,1815,1840]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Myrceugenia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="14E1EAC0FFE31017F7C18E77AA72A12F" box="[187,334,1815,1840]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Myrceugenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp., 
<taxonomicName id="E1954D51FFE31017F6E98E77A978A12F" authorityName="Burret" authorityYear="1941" box="[403,580,1814,1840]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Luma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apiculata">
<emphasis id="14E1EAC0FFE31017F6E98E77A978A12F" box="[403,580,1814,1840]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Luma apiculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E1954D51FFE31017F5068E76A85AA12F" authorityName="Cav" authorityYear="1798" box="[636,870,1814,1840]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Eucryphia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cordifolia">
<emphasis id="14E1EAC0FFE31017F5068E76A85AA12F" box="[636,870,1814,1840]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Eucryphia cordifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The 
<typeStatus id="F92E8870FFE31017F4D28E76AF36A12F" box="[936,1034,1814,1840]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">holotype</typeStatus>
specimen was collected on flowers of an isolated 
<taxonomicName id="E1954D51FFE31017F64F8E5BAAFDA14B" authorityName="Cav" authorityYear="1798" box="[309,449,1850,1876]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Eucryphia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cordifolia">
<emphasis id="14E1EAC0FFE31017F64F8E5BAAFDA14B" box="[309,449,1850,1876]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. cordifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tree at mid-day in semi-clouded weather.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="262A36D2FFE31017F7BD8E3EAE4BA183" blockId="4.[151,1437,1346,1949]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis id="14E1EAC0FFE31017F7BD8E3EAA36A167" bold="true" box="[199,266,1886,1912]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Notes</emphasis>
: the new species has damage in the legs produced by bad manipulation of collector. Hind legs are complete, but mid legs are totally missing. In addition, fore legs present both femora, but tibiae and tarsi are absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
